one thing that those of us who do a LOT of ae grouping learn is that all enchanters are not made the same.  Two lvl 60 enchanters with similar gear can be miles apart in skill.  I can't really explain why this is (although there are a few factors I can name) but when you make AE groups a lot you would be well served to keep a list of relative skill.  Some enchanters can keep a huge number of mobs locked while others cant keep 10.<br>
<br>
some things to look for.<br>
<br>
Turn on showspelleffects but turn particle density off.  You can watch the chanters and see how fast their stuns are going off.  If one is stunning a LOT less than the other, he is either not very smart or is very lagged (neither being a good thing).<br>
<br>
watch for AE tash and don't let them do it.  This is suicide to enchanters in AE groups.  The only thing that keeps AE groups alive is multiple layered stunning, tash doesnt help that.  If you have 50 mobs in stun lock your probably going to get 4 to 12 resists per cast and AE tash wont reduce that much.  Further, the cast time on tash leaves an opening in the stun cycle where mobs aren't being layered with stun, this almost always leads to a momentary loss of lock where a beat down and relock has to occur.<br>
<br>
watch for chanters that dont move.  Unless you are using facing chanters across a path, your chanters are going to be constnatly pushing mobs away from them in the direction they are facing.  Chanters that stay where they are at as the mobs move farther away are asking for it.  Once mobs move out of stun range they will RUSH that chanter as soon as the current stun wears off.  This interupts the casts and predictable results follow.<br>
<br>
these are just some of the things ive noticed and thought I'd pass on to people jsut getting into AE grouping.  Feel free to add any advice to this based on your experiences.<br>
<br>
<br>
Dhalamar<br>
Wiz 60 (52 AA Points) - The Mystical Order<br>
